Custom exception types.

When none of the standard exception types communicates enough, write your own. The convention is to extend Runtime Exception for an unchecked exception, or to extend Exception for a checked one. Provide constructors that accept a message string and an optional cause. The cause is another throwable that explains why this exception was raised.

For a domain example, an Insufficient Funds Exception might extend Runtime Exception, hold the requested amount and the available balance as fields, and produce a clean error message in the super call. Throwing it gives you a domain specific signal that any layer in the stack can catch. The fields let the caller introspect the exception programmatically, not just read its message.
